{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537184"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15911"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606213"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:09:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:09:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15911"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15911"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.52,0.23,0.09,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8602"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63111"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8602"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48562"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"5470"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20606"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63111"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting to participate in a clinical trial for a new medication to treat rheumatoid arthritis. She has had rheumatoid arthritis for eight years, currently well-controlled on methotrexate. She does not take any other regular medications. She works as a research nurse and is interested in clinical trials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe trial is comparing a new biological agent to standard therapy. It will involve 800 participants across 40 centres, with participants randomised to either the new medication or placebo in addition to their current treatment. The primary outcome is disease activity at 12 months. Participants and investigators will be blinded to treatment allocation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate phase of this clinical trial?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Phase 4","Phase 3","Phase 2","Phase 1","Pilot study"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a classic phase 3 clinical trial. The key features that identify this as \u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 3\u003C/strong\u003E include the large sample size, multiple study centres, randomised controlled design, and focus on confirming efficacy in a broader population. Phase 3 trials are typically conducted after safety and preliminary efficacy have been established in earlier phases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 1\u003C/strong\u003E would typically involve a small number of healthy volunteers (20-100) and focus primarily on safety, tolerability, and pharmacokinetics of the new drug. This would be conducted much earlier in drug development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 2\u003C/strong\u003E would involve a moderate number of patients (100-300) and focus on determining optimal dosing and providing preliminary evidence of efficacy. These studies are typically shorter in duration and may compare different doses rather than against placebo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhase 4\u003C/strong\u003E would occur after the drug has already been approved and is being used in clinical practice. These studies focus on long-term safety and effectiveness in real-world settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epilot study\u003C/strong\u003E would be a small-scale preliminary study conducted to evaluate feasibility, time, cost, adverse events, and effect size in order to predict an appropriate sample size and improve upon the study design prior to performance of a full-scale research project.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhase 3 trials are considered the gold standard for establishing efficacy of new treatments. They typically involve hundreds to thousands of participants, are randomised and double-blinded, and use intention-to-treat analysis to maintain the benefits of randomisation. The large sample size allows for detection of less common adverse effects and provides more precise estimates of treatment effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phase 3 clinical trials are large randomised controlled trials designed to confirm efficacy and monitor adverse effects in a broader population.","Sample size calculations are essential to ensure adequate statistical power to detect clinically meaningful differences between groups.","Intention-to-treat analysis is the preferred method for analysing phase 3 trial data to maintain randomisation and avoid bias."],"references":["Umscheid CA, Margolis DJ, Grossman CE. Key concepts of clinical trials: a narrative review. Postgrad Med. 2011;123(5):194-204. doi:10.3810/pgm.2011.09.2475"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48562"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15911"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48562","lin